              <h2>How the Colorado income tax calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                Colorado is one of the few states that uses a
                <strong>flat income tax rate</strong> instead of graduated
                brackets. That makes the math simpler, but real returns can
                still be confusing because of deductions, additions, and
                credits.
              </p>
              <p>
                This calculator focuses on the core pieces that drive most
                people’s Colorado state tax: your income, pre-tax deductions, an
                approximate deduction, the flat rate, and any credits you expect
                to claim.
              </p>

              <h3>Inputs you can control</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Filing status</strong> – Single, married filing
                  jointly, married filing separately, or head of household.
                  Colorado’s rate is flat, but we use status to suggest a
                  reasonable deduction amount.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Annual gross income</strong> – Your total income
                  before taxes and pre-tax contributions.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Pre-tax deductions</strong> – Things like 401(k),
                  403(b), traditional IRA, HSA, and some cafeteria-plan benefits
                  that reduce taxable income.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Deduction type and amount</strong> – Choose:
                  <ul>
                    <li>
                      <strong>Standard deduction (estimate)</strong> – Uses a
                      default amount based on filing status (you can still
                      override the number).
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <strong>Itemized deduction</strong> – Enter your own
                      estimate of itemized deductions.
                    </li>
                    <li>
                      <strong>No deduction</strong> – For quick “worst case”
                      scenarios.
                    </li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Colorado flat tax rate</strong> – Pre-filled with a
                  typical recent rate (e.g., around 4.40%). You can change this
                  if the law changes or for planning.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Colorado tax credits</strong> – Enter any state
                  credits you expect (e.g., earned income credit, child tax
                  credit, other refundable or nonrefundable credits).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Formulas used</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>1. Adjusted income</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Adjusted income} = \max(\text{Gross income} -
                  \text{Pre-tax deductions}, 0) \]
                </p>

                <p><strong>2. Colorado taxable income (approximate)</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{CO taxable income} = \max(\text{Adjusted income} -
                  \text{Deduction}, 0) \]
                </p>

                <p><strong>3. Preliminary Colorado tax</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Preliminary CO tax} = \text{CO taxable income} \times
                  \text{CO tax rate} \]
                </p>

                <p><strong>4. Final Colorado tax after credits</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Final CO tax} = \max(\text{Preliminary CO tax} -
                  \text{CO credits}, 0) \]
                </p>

                <p><strong>5. Effective Colorado tax rate</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Effective rate} = \begin{cases} 0 & \text{if gross
                  income} = 0 \\ \dfrac{\text{Final CO tax}}{\text{Gross
                  income}} & \text{otherwise} \end{cases} \]
                </p>

                <p><strong>6. After-tax income (Colorado only)</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{After-tax income} = \text{Gross income} - \text{Final
                  CO tax} \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>What this calculator does <em>not</em> cover</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Every Colorado-specific
                  <strong>addition or subtraction</strong> (e.g., detailed
                  retirement income exclusions, certain business adjustments).
                </li>
                <li>
                  All <strong>credits</strong> and their phase-outs – you can
                  enter a total credit amount, but the tool doesn’t compute each
                  credit from scratch.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Federal income tax</strong>, Social Security,
                  Medicare, or local taxes.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Complex situations like multi-state income,
                  nonresident/part-year resident allocations, or pass-through
                  entity elections.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For filing, always rely on the official Colorado forms and
                instructions or a qualified tax professional. Use this tool as a
                planning and education aid.
              </p>

              <h2>Colorado income tax basics</h2>
              <p>
                Colorado’s individual income tax is administered by the
                <strong>Colorado Department of Revenue</strong>. The state
                currently uses a <strong>single flat rate</strong> that applies
                to Colorado taxable income for all filing statuses.
              </p>

              <h3>Flat rate vs. tax brackets</h3>
              <p>
                In many states, your income is split across multiple brackets
                with different rates. Colorado is different:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  One <strong>flat rate</strong> applies to all of your Colorado
                  taxable income.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Your <strong>effective rate</strong> (tax ÷ gross income) is
                  usually a bit lower than the flat rate because of deductions
                  and credits.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Filing status still matters for federal taxes and for some
                  Colorado calculations, but not for the basic state rate.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Colorado taxable income (high-level view)</h3>
              <p>
                On your actual return, Colorado taxable income is based on your
                <strong>federal taxable income</strong>, plus or minus
                Colorado-specific additions and subtractions. This calculator
                approximates that by starting from your gross income and
                subtracting:
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>Pre-tax contributions (401(k), HSA, etc.).</li>
                <li>An estimated standard or itemized deduction.</li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                That gives a reasonable planning estimate for most wage earners,
                but it will not match every line of your return.
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions about Colorado income tax</h2>

              <h3>Is Colorado a high-tax state?</h3>
              <p>
                Colorado’s flat income tax rate is
                <strong>moderate</strong> compared with other states. Some
                states have no income tax at all, while others have top brackets
                above 10%. Colorado also has
                <strong>state and local sales taxes</strong> and
                <strong>property taxes</strong> that affect your total tax
                burden.
              </p>

              <h3>Do I owe Colorado tax if I work in another state?</h3>
              <p>
                It depends on your <strong>residency status</strong> and where
                the income is sourced:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Colorado residents generally pay Colorado tax on
                  <strong>all income</strong>, no matter where it’s earned, with
                  credits for taxes paid to other states.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Nonresidents usually pay Colorado tax only on
                  <strong>Colorado-source income</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Part-year residents file as such and allocate income between
                  states.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This calculator assumes you are a full-year Colorado resident
                and does not allocate multi-state income.
              </p>

              <h3>How can I lower my Colorado income tax bill?</h3>
              <p>Common strategies include:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Maximizing
                  <strong>pre-tax retirement contributions</strong> (401(k),
                  403(b), traditional IRA if deductible).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Using an <strong>HSA</strong> if you have a high-deductible
                  health plan.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Tracking <strong>itemized deductions</strong> (mortgage
                  interest, charitable contributions, certain taxes) if they
                  exceed the standard deduction.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Claiming all <strong>eligible Colorado credits</strong> (e.g.,
                  child tax credit, earned income credit, education-related
                  credits when available).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Use the calculator to see how changes in contributions,
                deductions, or credits affect your estimated Colorado tax.
              </p>

              <h3>When are Colorado income tax returns due?</h3>
              <p>
                Colorado generally follows the
                <strong>federal filing deadline</strong> (typically April 15, or
                the next business day if that falls on a weekend or holiday).
